			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">You could actually shorten up your code some and quit looking for the entire string. $word1,2,3 ect arnt accessable inside of the pluginmain dir . but what i did was take $realcase which is the entire incomming message with 1 extra char in the front. used an example from basic bot for this start out like this under your globals.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Code:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="code">
<br />
$msg = substr&#40;$realcase, 1&#41;;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;//the 1 at the end will strip off the extra letter
<br />
$word = explode&#40;&quot; &quot;,$msg&#41;;&nbsp; &nbsp;//didnt add any place holder for $word&#91;0&#93; so first word 
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; //isnt $word&#91;1&#93; but 
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; //instead it is $word&#91;0&#93; not too hard to figure out/remember.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This made it much easier. When i used $words i had to set a variable first anyways = to the string i wanted to check for instance had to look like this
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Code:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="code">
<br />
global $cloak_on_message, $words;
<br />

<br />
$cloak_on_message = &quot;turned the cloaking device in your city on.&quot;;
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp;
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; if &#40;$words == &quot;$cloak_on_message&quot;&#41;&#123;&#125;
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
So now that i exploded the incomming message it reduced alot of my time typing <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="Wink" border="0" /> and makes it look neater.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Code:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="code">
<br />
globals $realcase, $word;
<br />

<br />
$msg = substr&#40;$realcase, 1&#41;;
<br />
$word = explode&#40;&quot; &quot;, $msg&#41;;
<br />

<br />
if &#40;word&#91;8&#93; == &quot;on.&quot;&#41;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; //actually word 9 but -1 because first word is word&#91;0&#93;/
<br />
&#123; your code&#125;
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
you shouldnt have to worry about single word checks messing up. The chances that empty($sender) sending another message with 9th word beeing (on.) are verry unlikely.
<br />
 
<br />
With $words it allready parsed out the first word so you couldnt add the playername to the broadcast for enabling/disabling the cloak. You could use $firstword as thats global as i started to do but went about it this way instead. 
<br />

<br />
Using this i also wrote another plugin for the bot that allows me to check last attack that happened, last person enabled or disabled the cloak and all timestamped. so you can tell if it was a initiated attack or a random one. Also i tell my guys that the person leading the attack has to make sure the shields get put back up and CC healed before they log. So i can tell if they just logged off or did what they were suposed to do.
<br />

<br />
I kept this in the loop.php file. I have a few friends that run org bots as well and dont know any php. So i wanted the file to be easialy ported in if they wanted this feature to.  So all they have to do is copy the files over turn the loopback plugin on and they are done.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
